#### Collaborating using Github can be messy if you don\'92t really know what\'92s going on\
Although I\'92ve used git a lot for personal projects, I\'92ve had limited experience working in a team on this platform. As a lone worker, you rarely have to deal with things many of the more complicated git features, like remembering to pull from the remote to update your local copy with whatever your team mate did, or resolving merge conflicts. In my team, we had a lack of understanding about committing, pulling and pushing workflows (I still do, frankly), and ended up with some really messy commit histories as a result. After some useful conversations with a fellow S2DSer about best practices (he recommend we branch often, or get used to using pull requests) we tidied up our workflow somewhat. It\'92s possible to muddle along with git without really knowing what\'92s going on under the hood, but I\'92d really like to develop a thorough understanding of how it works. [This]() blog post I found might help with that.\
